table.column: Become a local Singaporean for a day: See how the locals live!

It is always fun to get the glimpse of a city like the locals. Being a tourist and hopping on a tourist bus and running by the tourist guide are not always fun at all. Why follow rules on a vacation when you can cut all the ropes and behave like a local c

<p>It is always fun to get the glimpse of a city like the locals. Being a tourist and hopping on a tourist bus and running by the tourist guide are not always fun at all. Why follow rules on a vacation when you can cut all the ropes and behave like a local citizen of that place and explore the city on your own terms?</p><p>And where else to begin such an adventure than the mesmerising Singapore! Becoming a local Singaporean for a day and exploring the city on your own terms will give you a happy high as never before. You can go wherever you want to, eat whatever you want to, and interact with anyone you want to.</p><p>The official language of Singapore is Mandarin Chinese, which even the local Singaporeans get to learn after a lot of difficulties! It is one of the most difficult languages there is in the whole world so do not feel bummed if you cannot speak in Mandarin Chinese fluently!</p><p>Leave the local dialect aside; you can do almost everything that the local people of Singapore do.</p><p>First and foremost, you need to find a local Singaporean who can show you around the day-to-day lives of the people of Singapore. If you cannot find a local &ldquo;friend&rdquo; in Singapore, try to crash at a local&rsquo;s house by opting from the options at Craigslist and similar couch hopping websites. What&rsquo;s best than to actually live with a Singaporean family and getting to know their lifestyle and culture as a first-hand experience! And coming back to the topic of the local dialect of Singapore, this family can be your key towards learning a whole new language! Well, at least you can give it a fair shot!</p><p>Also, stop dressing up like you are from a foreign land. You must not look like a tourist if you want to live like a local Singaporean! Put away those shiny shoes and jazzy pants, dress like a local person if you want to actually feel like you are doing this the right way. Dress up in a manner that you seep into the city like a chameleon!</p><p>Now that you have a place to live, find a place to eat! Eat like a local Singaporean at the local eateries and gorge on some amazing food. You will get to eat some of the most authentic and delicious Singaporean dishes at these places. Try and increase your observation power at these places and learn how the local Singaporeans order their food; their dialect and mannerism and try to copy that, to get the feels! This is also applicable while shopping at the local markets. We all know that Singapore is a mecca for all street-shopping lovers and if you manage to shop like a local Singaporean, you will be very happy and content with your purchases by the end of your day. Observe the local people shopping and pick their way of bargaining with the shopkeeper and do that yourself too. You will be surprised at yourself for being so good at behaving like a local person of a strange city!</p><p>Let us come back to the language thing once again! Another way in which you can master the fluency in Mandarin Chinese is by offering the local people of Singapore with a &ldquo;language exchange&rdquo;. &nbsp;You can ask them to teach you their language while you can teach them your language! It will be super fun and also, you will make a lot of good friends by the end of the day and all in all have a great time joking around the city, interacting with the local Singaporeans and learning their local language, their idioms and sayings, and even some cool verbal slang if they are willing to teach you!</p><p>One thing that you must refrain on a day like this is keeping yourself from hitting a place or a club or a restaurant of your nationality. It will create utter clashing in your life at that moment and you do not want that at any cost. Do not go to Little India or that corner American beer pub. You will not be able to live up to you &ldquo;local Singaporean&rdquo; day, if you try to mix up cultures.</p><p>Singapore is known as Asia&rsquo;s favorite playground; take advantage of this and go on a beach or a popular hangout zone and interact with the families there. Fish spas and underwater world are other options that you can try. You can turn your hobby into a great adventure by doing it along with a local Singaporean and having a lot of fun too.</p><p>Another thing that Singapore is famous for is the walking tours and the biking tours. Dedicated groups allow you to travel with them all around Singapore on foot or on a bike and take in the beauty of this beautiful city in slow motion. You can register for one such group with the destination of your choice and have a great chance at hanging out with some cool Singaporeans and interacting with them on the way. They will be able to guide you better than your tour guide and tell you about the places on your bike/walk tour, which no book can ever tell you. Also, throw away that Singapore Guide that you bought before going to Singapore. It will only confuse you and not let you enjoy the freedom of the city.</p><p>Oh, we forgot to mention about your traveling! While trying to live like a local Singaporean, you should always try to take the local bus that is surprisingly comfortable and very cheap to get from one place to another. You can easily strike up a conversation with local people on board and ask them for suggestions about which place you should go to eat or where you should spend the next day. Local Singaporeans are happy and hospitable people and they will happy to help you with your &ldquo;local&rdquo; experience in their lovely city.</p><p>The most important thing that you must follow on a day like this is not to step over the line when it comes to following the cultural ethics of Singapore. The city might be very modern and advanced, but it has certain ethics and you will not be liked if you do not adhere to them. For example, do not eat or drink while on a local transport. Singapore is one the safest places in the world, for both men and women; so do not worry about getting lost or getting hurt while you are on your own in this city. Nothing except for happiness will happen to you!</p><p>Spend your &ldquo;I am a local Singaporean&rdquo; day in such a manner that the tourists ask you for directions and advice! You will be surprised at how deeply satisfying and exuberayting experience it will be for you to spend a day in the dazzling city of Singapore as one of its own.</p>

table.column: Visit popular attractions such as Jurong Bird Park or Singapore Zoo where you will find more than 3000 animals from over 250 species.

table.name: reviews
table.column: Take a trip to Sentosa Island to enjoy fun for all the family. Meet the pink dolphins at Underwater World\'s Dolphin Lagoon or explore Singapore\'s colonial history at Fort Siloso.

table.name: reviews
table.column: Indeed, it\'s easy to live it up in Singapore with a host of attractions, beaches, facilities, excellent shopping and an air of excitement that pulses all day long.

table.name: reviews
table.column: Climate is not a major consideration when planning a holiday in Singapore as the temperature hovers around 29 degrees Celsius most of the time and the islands get fairly steady rainfall all year round.

table.name: reviews
table.column: Singapore is hot and humid, so light, loose-fitting clothing should be worn. Most Singaporeans dress fairly conservatively. Be sure to have hats and sunscreen on hand to protect your family from the hot, tropical sun.

table.name: reviews
table.column: The view was very nice. You willl see more of singapore that you wouldnt even notice if you will take a walk along the streets. The crew was so nice that we had a lot of photos together as souvenir.

table.name: reviews
table.column: We had the river cruise as our final tour. After a tiring day of walking, we again saw the beauty of singapore at a different perspective. Through a cruise.

table.name: reviews
table.column: The scenery is breathtaking especially at night. The lights were all up just like diamonds.. A very much suggested trip for those who will visit Singapore.

table.name: reviews
table.column: This is a great and cheap way to see the city. After all the walking Iam sure your do this is a great way to sight see whilst resting the legs. Highly recommended.

table.name: reviews
table.column: Flowing through Singapore City, it is a very convenient way to explore Singapore\'s most amazing parts through river boat specially in the evening and night.

table.name: reviews
table.column: The view of the whole city from a moving little boat was such an awesome one.

table.name: reviews
table.column: The view of the city is nice to look at specially that you will not gonna see it on such angles when you are walking along the streets.

table.name: reviews
table.column: Saw a different view of Singapore city part and things you may not otherwise see. my friends and I really enjoyed the trip. the \"sailor\" was so nice that he even had a wacky pose with us!

table.name: reviews
table.column: We visited in Feb 2014 and took a boat cruise under all the bridges and up next to the Merlion. It\'s a great way to see the city.

table.name: reviews
table.column: You can see all the new buildings and Marina Bay and the huge barge for special events.

table.name: reviews
table.column: There are two kinds of boat rides one can take.. The information provided about the fishes etc is very interesting specially the trivia. There is a massive enclosure where you can spot various fishes.

table.name: reviews
table.column: This trip was also fun! Was able to see different species of fish and river creatures and read/discovered fun facts about them. My favorite would be the giant crocodile, piranhas, the red panda, Kai-Kai the big panda.

table.name: reviews
table.column: We did both the Cruise and Amazon River Quest and loved both.

table.name: reviews
table.column: You can easily finish the whole place in 3 hours. One could see more marine life at the SEA Aquarium.

table.name: reviews
table.column: I love Pandas and this is basically the reason why we decided to visit River Safari. Prior the visit, I was only thinking of the Pandas as the main/major attraction but as we went inside, other animals were also very interesting.

table.name: reviews
table.column: We visited River Safari first. It is very scenic with great photo backdrop opportunities of the river. There were a great variety of animals and wildlife to see to keep us entertained.

table.name: reviews
table.column: Before you step onto a boat, you are taken on an adventure through various types of aquatic life.

table.name: reviews
table.column: The River Safari has some interesting critters in 1rst class enclosures and aquariums. The landscaping is beautiful and there is a lot to see and learn.

table.name: reviews
table.column: This place is very well set up with easy to navigate path with lots of sign boards to describe the exhibit. Our favourites are red panda and the giant pandas, Kai Kai and Jia Jia.

table.name: reviews
